The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To move forward in the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of the bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space with an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important are the bee’s composite eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately translates into collision prevention.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by rotating its wheels at a right or larger angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can’t be deflected up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allow it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, as well as acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require storing information or intuitive logic from previous manoeuvres, so it can run continuously with just a couple of dozens of KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about memory gigas, not even mega.”
This is the first step in developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan will introduce into the series cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in the way.
